    </div>

    <p>The challenge with iron supplementation has always been side effects. Traditional ferrous sulfate — the most commonly prescribed form — causes constipation, nausea, stomach pain, and metallic taste in 30-50% of users. These side effects are so unpleasant that studies show 40-60% of patients prescribed iron supplements stop taking them within the first month. Modern iron gummies solve this compliance crisis by using gentle iron forms that are better absorbed and far better tolerated.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Ferrous Bisglycinate</strong>
        <p>Gold standard gentle iron. Chelated with glycine for 2-4x better absorption than sulfate. 70% fewer GI side effects. Can be taken with food with minimal absorption loss. Premium but worth it for anemia correction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Ferric Pyrophosphate</strong>
        <p>Slow-release form that dissolves gradually over hours. Minimizes the acute GI exposure that causes nausea. Used in food fortification because it does not affect taste, color, or texture.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Carbonyl Iron</strong>
        <p>Pure elemental iron with very slow, controlled absorption. Virtually non-toxic at standard doses — one of the safest iron forms for home supplementation. Lower bioavailability requires higher doses.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Vitamin C (absorption enhancer)</strong>
        <p>Increases iron absorption by 2-6x by converting ferric to ferrous iron. Every iron gummy should include vitamin C or be taken with a vitamin C source. This is the single most effective strategy for maximizing iron uptake.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2020 landmark study in <em>The Lancet Haematology</em> found that <strong>alternate-day iron dosing (every other day) was as effective as daily dosing</strong> for correcting iron deficiency anemia — with <strong>significantly fewer GI side effects</strong>. This finding is attributed to hepcidin cycling: iron absorption triggers hepcidin release, which blocks further absorption for 24-48 hours. By dosing every other day, each dose encounters lower hepcidin levels, resulting in higher fractional absorption per dose.</p>
      <cite>The Lancet Haematology, 2020 — Alternate-day iron dosing</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>Absorption Tips That Double Your Iron Uptake</h3>

    <p>The difference between effective and ineffective iron supplementation often comes down to absorption optimization. Taking iron with vitamin C can increase absorption by 2-6x. Conversely, taking iron with dairy, coffee, or calcium can reduce absorption by 40-60%. These simple timing adjustments can mean the difference between hemoglobin recovery in 4 weeks versus 12 weeks — or no recovery at all.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>The OJ rule:</strong> Take your iron gummy with a glass of orange juice (84mg vitamin C per 8oz). This single habit can increase iron absorption by 200-600%. Avoid coffee, tea, dairy, and calcium supplements within 2 hours of your iron dose. The absorption difference between optimal and suboptimal timing can be as much as 10-fold.</p>
    </div>

