    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Iron Gummies for Anemia</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best form of iron for anemia in gummies?</summary><p>Ferrous bisglycinate — chelated with glycine for 2-4x better absorption and 70% fewer GI side effects than ferrous sulfate. Ferric pyrophosphate is a good gentle alternative. Avoid ferrous sulfate in gummy format.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much iron do I need if I have anemia?</summary><p>The therapeutic dose is 100-200mg daily for moderate-to-severe anemia. Recent research shows alternate-day dosing of 60mg may be equally effective. Most iron gummies provide 10-27mg, appropriate for mild deficiency and maintenance.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take iron gummies to work for anemia?</summary><p>Hemoglobin rises within 2-4 weeks. Full recovery requires 2-3 months. Continue 3+ additional months after normalization to rebuild stores. Do not stop when hemoglobin normalizes.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do iron gummies cause constipation?</summary><p>Gentle forms (bisglycinate, pyrophosphate) cause significantly less constipation than ferrous sulfate — 70% fewer GI effects. Staying hydrated, eating fiber, and pairing with vitamin C also helps.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take iron gummies on an empty stomach?</summary><p>For best absorption, yes — 1 hour before or 2 hours after eating. Bisglycinate can be taken with food with minimal absorption loss. Avoid dairy, coffee, tea, and calcium within 2 hours.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can iron gummies replace prescription iron?</summary><p>For mild deficiency, yes. For moderate-to-severe anemia (hemoglobin below 10), prescription doses (100-200mg) or IV iron may be needed. Most gummies provide 10-27mg — the lower therapeutic range.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What foods help iron gummies absorb better?</summary><p>Vitamin C increases absorption 2-6x. Take with orange juice, strawberries, or bell peppers. Avoid dairy, coffee, tea, whole grains, and calcium supplements within 2 hours — they can reduce absorption by 40-60%.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Who is most at risk for iron deficiency anemia?</summary><p>Menstruating women (10% prevalence), pregnant women (doubled RDA), vegetarians/vegans (lower absorption from plant iron), endurance athletes, and individuals with GI conditions (celiac, IBD, gastric bypass).</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Important:</strong> Iron supplements can be toxic in overdose — especially for children. Store iron gummies in child-resistant containers out of reach. If you suspect overdose, call Poison Control (1-800-222-1222). Women with hemochromatosis should not supplement iron. Always confirm iron deficiency with blood work (CBC + ferritin) before supplementing — excess iron accumulation is harmful.</p>
    </div>

